<Link id="l00266" /><CodeLine lineNumber="266"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// A POD-like structure that we use to store a global reference together with</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00267" /><CodeLine lineNumber="267"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// its metadata types. In this pass we frequently need to query the set of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00268" /><CodeLine lineNumber="268"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// metadata types referenced by a global, which at the IR level is an expensive</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00269" /><CodeLine lineNumber="269"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// operation involving a map lookup; this data structure helps to reduce the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="270"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// number of times we need to do this lookup.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/anonymous-namespace-lowertypetests-cpp-/globaltypemember"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/anonymous-namespace-lowertypetests-cpp-/globaltypemember">GlobalTypeMember</a> final : TrailingObjects&lt;GlobalTypeMember, MDNode &#42;&gt; &#123;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="277"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// For functions: true if the jump table is canonical. This essentially means</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="278"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// whether the canonical address (i.e. the symbol table entry) of the function</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00279" /><CodeLine lineNumber="279"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// is provided by the local jump table. This is normally the same as whether</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00280" /><CodeLine lineNumber="280"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the function is defined locally, but if canonical jump tables are disabled</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00281" /><CodeLine lineNumber="281"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// by the user then the jump table never provides a canonical definition.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00282" /><CodeLine lineNumber="282"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">bool</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> IsJumpTableCanonical;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="284"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// For functions: true if this function is either defined or used in a thinlto</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="285"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// module and its jumptable entry needs to be exported to thinlto backends.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00764" /><CodeLine lineNumber="764"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00765" /><CodeLine lineNumber="765"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// We need to check that the offset both falls within our range and is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00766" /><CodeLine lineNumber="766"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// suitably aligned. We can check both properties at the same time by</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00767" /><CodeLine lineNumber="767"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// performing a right rotate by log2(alignment) followed by an integer</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00768" /><CodeLine lineNumber="768"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// comparison against the bitset size. The rotate will move the lower</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00769" /><CodeLine lineNumber="769"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// order bits that need to be zero into the higher order bits of the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00770" /><CodeLine lineNumber="770"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// result, causing the comparison to fail if they are nonzero. The rotate</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00771" /><CodeLine lineNumber="771"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// also conveniently gives us a bit offset to use during the load from</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00829" /><CodeLine lineNumber="829"><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">void</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> LowerTypeTestsModule::buildBitSetsFromGlobalVariables(</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00831" /><CodeLine lineNumber="831"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Build a new global with the combined contents of the referenced globals.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00832" /><CodeLine lineNumber="832"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This global is a struct whose even-indexed elements contain the original</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00834" /><CodeLine lineNumber="834"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// any padding required to align the next element to the next power of 2 plus</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00849" /><CodeLine lineNumber="849"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordFlow">if</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> (GVOffset != 0) &#123;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00851" /><CodeLine lineNumber="851"><span class="doxyHighlight">      GlobalInits.push&#95;back(</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00856" /><CodeLine lineNumber="856"><span class="doxyHighlight">    uint64&#95;t InitSize = <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/arm/armslshardening-cpp/#ad467c4ab9119043f9b7750ab986be61a">DL</a>.getTypeAllocSize(GV-&gt;getValueType());</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00860" /><CodeLine lineNumber="860"><span class="doxyHighlight">    DesiredPadding = <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#afb65eef479f0473d0fe1666b80155237">NextPowerOf2</a>(InitSize - 1) - InitSize;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00861" /><CodeLine lineNumber="861"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00862" /><CodeLine lineNumber="862"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Experiments of different caps with Chromium on both x64 and ARM64</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00863" /><CodeLine lineNumber="863"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// have shown that the 32-byte cap generates the smallest binary on</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00864" /><CodeLine lineNumber="864"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// both platforms while different caps yield similar performance.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00865" /><CodeLine lineNumber="865"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// (see https://lists.llvm.org/pipermail/llvm-dev/2018-July/124694.html)</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01567" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1567"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Given a disjoint set of type identifiers and functions, build a jump table</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01568" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1568"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// for the functions, build the bit sets and lower the llvm.type.test calls.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01569" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1569"><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">void</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> LowerTypeTestsModule::buildBitSetsFromFunctionsNative(</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01570" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1570"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab9c6b351507d3c0730f4290919d43a12">ArrayRef&lt;Metadata &#42;&gt;</a> TypeIds, <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab9c6b351507d3c0730f4290919d43a12">ArrayRef&lt;GlobalTypeMember &#42;&gt;</a> Functions) &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01571" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1571"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Unlike the global bitset builder, the function bitset builder cannot</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01572" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1572"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// re-arrange functions in a particular order and base its calculations on the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01573" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1573"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// layout of the functions&#39; entry points, as we have no idea how large a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01574" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1574"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// particular function will end up being (the size could even depend on what</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01575" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1575"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// this pass does!) Instead, we build a jump table, which is a block of code</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01576" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1576"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// consisting of one branch instruction for each of the functions in the bit</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01577" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1577"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// set that branches to the target function, and redirect any taken function</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01578" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1578"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// addresses to the corresponding jump table entry. In the object file&#39;s</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01579" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1579"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// symbol table, the symbols for the target functions also refer to the jump</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01580" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1580"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// table entries, so that addresses taken outside the module will pass any</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01581" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1581"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// verification done inside the module.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01582" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1582"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01583" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1583"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// In more concrete terms, suppose we have three functions f, g, h which are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01584" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1584"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// of the same type, and a function foo that returns their addresses:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01585" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1585"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01586" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1586"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// f:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01587" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1587"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// mov 0, %eax</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01588" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1588"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ret</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01589" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1589"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01590" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1590"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// g:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01591" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1591"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// mov 1, %eax</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01592" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1592"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ret</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01593" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1593"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01594" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1594"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// h:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01595" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1595"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// mov 2, %eax</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01596" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1596"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ret</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01597" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1597"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01598" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1598"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// foo:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01599" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1599"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// mov f, %eax</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01600" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1600"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// mov g, %edx</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01601" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1601"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// mov h, %ecx</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01602" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1602"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ret</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01603" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1603"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01604" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1604"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// We output the jump table as module-level inline asm string. The end result</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01608" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1608"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// g = .cfi.jumptable + 4</span></CodeLine>
